01:00:53.270 --> 01:00:54.570
to get the last part of it.

01:00:54.570 --> 01:00:57.610
You said comics are the
21st century's most potent,

01:00:57.610 --> 01:00:58.910
and I just wanted
to get the rest.

01:00:58.910 --> 01:01:00.210
&gt;&gt; Charles Brownstein:
Oh, form of literature.

01:01:00.210 --> 01:01:01.510
&gt;&gt; Okay, thank you.

01:01:01.510 --> 01:01:02.810
&gt;&gt; Charles Brownstein: There
was another one over here.

01:01:02.810 --> 01:01:04.110
Yes.

01:01:04.110 --> 01:01:07.240
&gt;&gt; Have you seen, now we're
seeing actual novels being

01:01:07.240 --> 01:01:09.510
converted into graphic
novels and things like that.

01:01:09.510 --> 01:01:12.240
Have you seen and has
there ever been a case

01:01:12.240 --> 01:01:15.610
where a graphic novel
has, somebody has gone

01:01:15.610 --> 01:01:18.330
after the graphic novels
and not the original novel?

01:01:18.330 --> 01:01:19.630
&gt;&gt; Charles Brownstein: Yeah,
that's a good question.

01:01:19.630 --> 01:01:22.550
The question was that
there are now an abundance

01:01:22.550 --> 01:01:26.490
of graphic novels that
are, that come from novels

01:01:26.490 --> 01:01:29.430
that they've been adapted
from the novel form

01:01:29.430 --> 01:01:30.730
and have I seen any cases

01:01:30.730 --> 01:01:33.760
where the graphic novel has been
challenged and not the original.

01:01:33.760 --> 01:01:35.650
Yes, in fact, the fund
has been very active

01:01:35.650 --> 01:01:38.270
in defending The Graveyard
Book graphic novel adaptation

01:01:38.270 --> 01:01:40.970
of Neil Gaiman's
prize-winning novel

01:01:40.970 --> 01:01:44.640
where the novel adaptation was
attacked in several localities

01:01:44.640 --> 01:01:47.620
because it addresses
the death of parents.

01:01:47.620 --> 01:01:49.650
And that being too
upsetting or inappropriate

01:01:49.650 --> 01:01:51.320
for the middle school audiences

01:01:51.320 --> 01:01:52.950
that are confronting
that material.

01:01:52.950 --> 01:01:54.250
&gt;&gt; Wait a minute.

01:01:54.250 --> 01:01:55.550
The graphic novel
is attacked but --

01:01:55.550 --> 01:01:56.850
&gt;&gt; Charles Brownstein:
But not the novel.

01:01:56.850 --> 01:01:58.150
&gt;&gt; I was going to say,

01:01:58.150 --> 01:01:59.510
and I guarantee you they
will let [inaudible] Bambi,

01:01:59.510 --> 01:02:00.810
which is --

01:02:00.810 --> 01:02:02.110
&gt;&gt; Charles Brownstein:
Yeah right.

01:02:02.110 --> 01:02:03.410
Yeah.

01:02:03.410 --> 01:02:08.830
&gt;&gt; As a continued thought,
are there formalized groups

01:02:08.830 --> 01:02:12.960
that are, like we
had in the past?

01:02:12.960 --> 01:02:14.720
&gt;&gt; Charles Brownstein: Sure, the
question is, are there any kind

01:02:14.720 --> 01:02:16.860
of formal pressure
groups that are going

01:02:16.860 --> 01:02:19.370
after graphic novels now
as there were in the past.

01:02:19.370 --> 01:02:21.010
And the answer, thank fully,

01:02:21.010 --> 01:02:24.000
is that not at the
moment that we are seeing.

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:26.980
However, there are
campaigns that happen

01:02:26.980 --> 01:02:30.040
in local environments
with great frequency.

01:02:30.040 --> 01:02:31.990
Some of the slides I had to pass

01:02:31.990 --> 01:02:36.740
over for time involve
media attacks on teachers

01:02:36.740 --> 01:02:39.650
and librarians that are making
graphic novels available.

01:02:39.650 --> 01:02:43.700
Earlier this year, we defended
a book edited by Ariel Schrag,

01:02:43.700 --> 01:02:46.160
an anthology called Stuck
in the Middle, which is,

01:02:46.160 --> 01:02:49.280
I think it was called 12
Stories from a Difficult Age.

01:02:49.280 --> 01:02:52.840
And it was anthology of stories
about being in middle school.

01:02:52.840 --> 01:02:55.730
And the mother of a middle
school kid that checked it

01:02:55.730 --> 01:02:57.470
out in the school library
where it had resided

01:02:57.470 --> 01:02:59.750
for the last ten
years or so objected

01:02:59.750 --> 01:03:03.550
because it depicted kids
smoking, and there was a scene

01:03:03.550 --> 01:03:05.300
where a kid talked
about his fantasy

01:03:05.300 --> 01:03:06.880
of how he would murder people.

01:03:06.880 --> 01:03:10.430
Which I guarantee you, if you've
ever met a 12-year-old boy,

01:03:10.430 --> 01:03:12.300
or 12-year-old, like
this is a thing

01:03:12.300 --> 01:03:13.600
that happens in their head.

01:03:13.600 --> 01:03:15.740
It wasn't just on the page.

01:03:15.740 --> 01:03:17.700
But they don't do it, right.

01:03:17.700 --> 01:03:20.550
It was a safe place to access
these feelings and emotions.

01:03:20.550 --> 01:03:24.260
And it was kind of talking
about everybody feels this way.

01:03:24.260 --> 01:03:26.220
So this parent didn't
just challenge the book,

01:03:26.220 --> 01:03:30.890
she went to the local TV station
that took the flagged copy,

01:03:30.890 --> 01:03:33.640
the parent's flagged copy of
the book and did the old saw

01:03:33.640 --> 01:03:35.430
of this book is so dangerous,

01:03:35.430 --> 01:03:37.230
we can't even show
you what's in it.

01:03:37.230 --> 01:03:39.890
You know, that stuff
happens with great frequency.

01:03:39.890 --> 01:03:41.290
And the fund is active

01:03:41.290 --> 01:03:44.360
in providing resources
both intellectually,

01:03:44.360 --> 01:03:47.290
and in some cases,
actually sending, you know,

01:03:47.290 --> 01:03:50.750
experts that we pay for in to
help deal with these situations.

01:03:50.750 --> 01:03:52.210
Was there on this side, yes.

01:03:52.210 --> 01:03:56.090
&gt;&gt; I grew up in a
dictatorship in Spain.

01:03:56.090 --> 01:04:00.020
And it had a very
active censorship office.

01:04:00.020 --> 01:04:04.640
And those two remind me
of the [inaudible] stuff.

01:04:04.640 --> 01:04:05.940
For example, [inaudible]

01:04:05.940 --> 01:04:11.670
which was the main comic book
publisher in Spain [inaudible].

01:04:11.670 --> 01:04:18.440
And I wanted to add also
that during the same period

01:04:18.440 --> 01:04:24.470
of the dictatorship, one of the
creators became very famous,

01:04:24.470 --> 01:04:27.510
and he created two
comic book [inaudible].

01:04:27.510 --> 01:04:31.550
And those comic books
defied today's dictatorship.

01:04:31.550 --> 01:04:35.870
I mean the censors
missed the big picture.

01:04:35.870 --> 01:04:39.650
Because usually we have
the [inaudible] story

01:04:39.650 --> 01:04:43.000
that you would defeat the
enemy, meaning the dictator.

01:04:43.000 --> 01:04:48.040
And he would establish sort of
like a local governance council.

01:04:48.040 --> 01:04:52.040
And the censorship
missed the big picture.

01:04:52.040 --> 01:04:55.130
And he was laughing at
[inaudible] in the 1990s.

01:04:55.130 --> 01:04:58.870
But yeah, they had to fight
those things, but for him,

01:04:58.870 --> 01:05:01.410
it was a way to fight
the dictatorship.

01:05:01.410 --> 01:05:03.780
And he was a communist,

01:05:03.780 --> 01:05:07.590
which means that in [inaudible]
it automatically means you're an

01:05:07.590 --> 01:05:09.540
enemy of the state.

01:05:09.540 --> 01:05:13.680
But he used those two comics,
the most popular comics

01:05:13.680 --> 01:05:18.120
in Spain, to fight the
dictatorship and the censorship.

01:05:18.120 --> 01:05:19.420
&gt;&gt; Charles Brownstein:
That's a great story.

01:05:19.420 --> 01:05:20.720
Thank you for --

01:05:20.720 --> 01:05:24.160
&gt;&gt; And I just recommend those
two titles for the library.

01:05:24.160 --> 01:05:25.960
&gt;&gt; Charles Brownstein:
And what are they?

01:05:25.960 --> 01:05:29.610
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

01:05:29.610 --> 01:05:34.070
&gt;&gt; [Foreign Language]
was created in 1956,

01:05:34.070 --> 01:05:37.710
and [Foreign Language]
was created in 1958.

01:05:37.710 --> 01:05:39.800
The first one was set
in the Middle Ages.

01:05:39.800 --> 01:05:44.070
The second one was set
in the [inaudible].

01:05:44.070 --> 01:05:45.690
&gt;&gt; Charles Brownstein:
Before I get to you, Shannon,

01:05:45.690 --> 01:05:47.060
thank you for sharing that.

01:05:47.060 --> 01:05:50.770
And it brings up a really
great aspect of comics

01:05:50.770 --> 01:05:53.420
in that their ability

01:05:53.420 --> 01:05:58.640
to be subversive is
very, very important.

01:05:58.640 --> 01:06:02.690
Whether it is these
example in Franco, Spain.

01:06:02.690 --> 01:06:08.230
Walt Kelly taking on Estes
Kefauver in the strip Pogo.

01:06:08.230 --> 01:06:14.330
You know, modern efforts of
editorial cartoonists that are,

01:06:14.330 --> 01:06:16.220
you know, in some cases really
putting their livelihood

01:06:16.220 --> 01:06:19.010
on the line by speaking
truth to power.

01:06:19.010 --> 01:06:21.380
You know, all are
contained within this medium.

01:06:21.380 --> 01:06:23.770
And for a long time,
because it was regarded

01:06:23.770 --> 01:06:26.860
as low value speech,
it was a place

01:06:26.860 --> 01:06:30.350
where people could really
give voice to these sorts

01:06:30.350 --> 01:06:33.660
of concerns either
about political justice

01:06:33.660 --> 01:06:36.570
or social justice and the way
that I shared the EC stories.

01:06:36.570 --> 01:06:40.120
And I think it continues
to perform that function.

01:06:40.120 --> 01:06:41.420
Shannon.

01:06:41.420 --> 01:06:42.720
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I was just curious,

01:06:42.720 --> 01:06:48.880
like '48 is where you said
all these laws were beginning

01:06:48.880 --> 01:06:51.980
to be passed against comics
and against publishers.

01:06:51.980 --> 01:06:53.280
I'm just wondering,

01:06:53.280 --> 01:06:56.110
what convictions were
happening at that time.

01:06:56.110 --> 01:06:58.130
Because until Mike
Diana came along,

01:06:58.130 --> 01:07:01.250
that's the first time I've
heard of a comic artist being --

01:07:01.250 --> 01:07:02.840
&gt;&gt; Charles Brownstein: Sure.

01:07:02.840 --> 01:07:05.470
So the question was with the
laws passed against comics

01:07:05.470 --> 01:07:08.630
in 1948, what's the
conviction record?

01:07:08.630 --> 01:07:11.540
And that's a very good question

01:07:11.540 --> 01:07:14.700
that there aren't
really good answers to.

01:07:14.700 --> 01:07:17.590
The first serious
conviction that I'm aware

01:07:17.590 --> 01:07:21.850
of involving the sale of
comics was the 1971 conviction

01:07:21.850 --> 01:07:26.680
of the New Yorker Bookstore
in the Zap number four case.

01:07:26.680 --> 01:07:30.690
Prior to that in the underground
comics there were a lot

01:07:30.690 --> 01:07:35.420
of cases brought against
head shops and bookstores

01:07:35.420 --> 01:07:37.670
that would sell underground
comics didn't make it all the

01:07:37.670 --> 01:07:38.970
way to court.

01:07:38.970 --> 01:07:41.650
Ron Turner, famous, the
publisher of Last Gasp,

01:07:41.650 --> 01:07:45.800
tells a story about a comic
book pungently entitled Felch

01:07:45.800 --> 01:07:49.490
which was the basis of a
prosecution in Long Beach,

01:07:49.490 --> 01:07:51.580
California, and it
was they were going

01:07:51.580 --> 01:07:53.160
to bust the store that sold it.

01:07:53.160 --> 01:07:55.510
And they were going to put
these guys in jail forever.

01:07:55.510 --> 01:07:58.550
But one of the cops stole it
because they wanted to pass it

01:07:58.550 --> 01:08:00.390
around the office, so it
never made it into evidence

01:08:00.390 --> 01:08:02.100
and the case was thrown out.

01:08:02.100 --> 01:08:04.290
There's a lot of stuff
like that that happened.

01:08:04.290 --> 01:08:07.700
The first one that really stuck
was this Zap number four case.

01:08:07.700 --> 01:08:13.070
The stuff in the
1940s and the 1950s

01:08:13.070 --> 01:08:16.770
after the Kefauver hearings were
really about being deterrents.

01:08:16.770 --> 01:08:19.450
They were about creating
an economic deterrent

01:08:19.450 --> 01:08:23.370
to distribution of the material
that was found objectionable.

01:08:23.370 --> 01:08:26.390
And in a lot of ways were
using the laws in a way

01:08:26.390 --> 01:08:27.690
that was unconstitutional.

01:08:27.690 --> 01:08:28.990
Because they were attempting

01:08:28.990 --> 01:08:31.680
to create a prior restraint
upon the freedom of expression.

01:08:31.680 --> 01:08:34.210
But there wasn't,
certainly there was no group

01:08:34.210 --> 01:08:39.170
like the funds and the ACLU,
while they spoke out for comics

01:08:39.170 --> 01:08:41.870
in the 1950s, and in particular,

01:08:41.870 --> 01:08:45.490
in the 1954 subcommittee
hearings, you know,

01:08:45.490 --> 01:08:46.790
wasn't really bringing cases

01:08:46.790 --> 01:08:49.080
against those sorts
of laws at the time.

01:08:49.080 --> 01:08:51.400
And I don't think it
would have helped anyway

01:08:51.400 --> 01:08:53.170
because the public
was so adamant

01:08:53.170 --> 01:08:57.170
that this stuff is a
danger to our youth

01:08:57.170 --> 01:08:58.770
that something needs
to be done about it.

01:08:58.770 --> 01:09:01.610
That the economics
dictated the code.

01:09:01.610 --> 01:09:03.030
Never forget, the
code is a creature

01:09:03.030 --> 01:09:05.100
of the comic book
industry first and foremost

01:09:05.100 --> 01:09:07.090
and always had been
throughout its time.

01:09:07.090 --> 01:09:09.630
There's on this side, and
then I'll get to you, Mike.

01:09:09.630 --> 01:09:11.430
Was there on this side?

01:09:11.430 --> 01:09:12.890
Okay, I'm sorry about
that, Mike.

01:09:12.890 --> 01:09:14.190
Go ahead.

01:09:14.190 --> 01:09:16.700
&gt;&gt; Oh, I was just going to say
the current comic [inaudible]

01:09:16.700 --> 01:09:20.180
and talks a little bit about
his trial first edition

01:09:20.180 --> 01:09:21.840
in World War I.

01:09:21.840 --> 01:09:27.080
So he was actually affected
and had economic consequences.

01:09:27.080 --> 01:09:32.110
&gt;&gt; But that was for violating
the then [inaudible] law.

01:09:32.110 --> 01:09:34.200
[ Overlapped Speaking ]

01:09:34.200 --> 01:09:36.530
It's still for his
cartoons, though Warren.

01:09:36.530 --> 01:09:38.000
&gt;&gt; Yes.

01:09:38.000 --> 01:09:39.650
&gt;&gt; So how do we actually
give you money, Charles.

01:09:39.650 --> 01:09:43.020
That was my main question.

01:09:43.020 --> 01:09:44.320
&gt;&gt; Charles Brownstein:
You can contribute

01:09:44.320 --> 01:09:46.040
to the Comic Book
Legal Defense Fund,

01:09:46.040 --> 01:09:47.830
and thank you for that, Mike.

01:09:47.830 --> 01:09:50.040
You can contribute to the
Comic Book Legal Defense Fund

01:09:50.040 --> 01:09:51.680
in a variety of ways.

01:09:51.680 --> 01:09:53.790
I actually have some
publications I'll be giving

01:09:53.790 --> 01:09:57.420
folks at the end of this where
you can sign up for membership.

01:09:57.420 --> 01:09:59.880
Membership is as little
as five bucks a year.

01:09:59.880 --> 01:10:01.440
And it does two things.

01:10:01.440 --> 01:10:04.530
It gives us the economic
resources we need

01:10:04.530 --> 01:10:06.970
to protect the people
that need protection.

01:10:06.970 --> 01:10:09.240
And it also gives us standing
in cases where we have

01:10:09.240 --> 01:10:11.440
to fight unconstitutional
legislation and can point

01:10:11.440 --> 01:10:14.420
to membership within
that environment.

01:10:14.420 --> 01:10:17.580
You can also support our work
by coming to SPX this weekend

01:10:17.580 --> 01:10:19.010
where we're going to
be having signings,

01:10:19.010 --> 01:10:21.760
and we've got graphic novels
available that are signed

01:10:21.760 --> 01:10:24.540
by their creators to
raise money for our work.

01:10:24.540 --> 01:10:26.300
But yeah, when we break up here,

01:10:26.300 --> 01:10:28.670
I'll pull the publications
out of the bag.

01:10:28.670 --> 01:10:30.010
We have our new brand
books [inaudible] handbook

01:10:30.010 --> 01:10:31.370
that I can give to everybody.

01:10:31.370 --> 01:10:33.830
And that has all of
our signup information.

01:10:33.830 --> 01:10:37.520
Whatever you can do to help,
whatever's within your budget,

01:10:37.520 --> 01:10:39.170
does help us achieve our book.

01:10:39.170 --> 01:10:41.830
We're a small staff of
three full-time folks,

01:10:41.830 --> 01:10:45.780
and a part-time editorial
director

01:10:45.780 --> 01:10:47.180
that does all of this work.

01:10:47.180 --> 01:10:49.260
And we pride ourselves
on being transparent

01:10:49.260 --> 01:10:51.230
and being good stewards
of your contributions.

01:10:51.230 --> 01:10:53.970
&gt;&gt; And you get an
awesome looking lapel pin.

01:10:53.970 --> 01:10:55.890
&gt;&gt; Charles Brownstein:
We do have good merch.

01:10:55.890 --> 01:11:00.540
Our Deputy Director Alex
Cox makes amazing merch.

